04023nam a22006375i 9780292747968DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221997txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927479687 a10.7560/7520472doi  a(DE-B1597)586552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0360102bisacsh1 aMonday, Jane Clements, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVoices from the Wild Horse Desert :bThe Vaquero Families of the King and Kenedy Ranches /cJane Clements Monday, Betty Bailey Colley. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Round 'Em Up, Move 'Em Out -- t2. From Longhorns to King Ranch Santa Cruz, Mustangs to Quarter Horses -- t3. Growing Up on the Wild Horse Desert -- t4. The Vaquero Family -- t5. Into the Twenty-first Century -- tAppendix A: Individuals Interviewed -- tAppendix B: Individuals Referenced -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFounded before the Civil War, the King and Kenedy Ranches have become legendary for their size, their wealth, and their endless herds of cattle. A major factor in the longevity of these ranches has always been the loyal workforce of vaqueros (Mexican and Mexican American cowboys) and their families. Some of the vaquero families have worked on the ranches through five or six generations. In this book, Jane Clements Monday and Betty Bailey Colley bring together the voices of these men and women who make ranching possible in the Wild Horse Desert. From 1989 to 1995, the authors interviewed more than sixty members of vaquero families, ranging in age from 20 to 93. Their words provide a panoramic view of ranch work and life that spans most of the twentieth century. The vaqueros and their families describe all aspects of life on the ranches, from working cattle and doing many kinds of ranch maintenance to the home chores of raising children, cooking, and cleaning. The elders recall a life of endless manual labor that nonetheless afforded the satisfaction of jobs done with skill and pride. The younger people describe how modernization has affected the ranches and changed the lifeways of the people who work there.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh1 aCastillo Crimm, Ana Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColley, Betty Bailey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCrimm, Carolina Castillo.1 aKleberg, Stephen J.1 aTio Kleberg, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75204740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292747968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292747968/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK